<br>
Nope. You are completely wrong.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A failure of a conventional booster tends to result in the loss of the payload and the occasional dropping of some metal chunks where they don't belong.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Tough luck if that payload happens to be human. The fuel can be rather toxic to the environment aswell.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A failure of an exotic nuclear booster would result in an horrible radiological catastrophe.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The location of the launch site must be taken into account. The poles would be unaffected by the worst possible case scenario (which might never happen at all). Deserts or mid ocean locations would be fine too. Many incredibly high yield fission devices designed specifically for maximum 'catastrophe' were detonated back in the 50's and 60's. They have had no measurable impact on society. A reactor difficulty is not even comparable to the smallest nuke going off. As long as the launch site is away from inhabited areas the danger is acceptable in my opinion.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A one hundred percent failure rate of chemical boosters are less destructive then a single nuclear booster failure.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A hundred manned chemical transports going the way of Challenger is better than a single nuclear reactor failure over a desolate part of the Earth's surface? Your attitude is the same one which led to Challenger occuring. The first attempt to send civilians up into space. Not the first to die because of flimsy feeble firework technology. Space travel will never become commonplace until rockets become safer. Safety requires power. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> You have made a serious mistake in confusing safety with reliability.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The crew of Challenger applaud you.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> You used the example of commercial Nuclear reactors. They are quite unreliable and equivalent performance in boosters would be disasterous.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What rot. Commercial reactors rarely suffer a meltdown. There are hundreds of reactors around the World running 24 hours a day decade after decade with no loss of life.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Power reactors use defense-in-depth to shield the public from the effects of the un-reliability. EBR-1 , Fermi-1, TMI-2, Chenobyl, etc wiped out their own cores.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Etc? Keep going. Give us the whole list. Let's see if they can be counted on two hands.<br>
