<br>
<br>
1)Yales: TMI-2 didn't destroy its own reactor, the human operators did.  Shutting off RCS flow from a reactor that is already overheating was a rather horrible idea.  <br>
     Also-I would like to say that 2 tons of U-235 is prolly pretty damn close to accurate for a commercial power plant, it might even be closer to 3.  The main point being missed here, I believe, is that a reactor being used on an atmosphere-launched craft would be considerably smaller than a commercial reactor and would be designed more or less from scratch.  As an example, NASA is leaning towards multi-phase heat transfer system of liquid-vapor components for cooling and heat transfer.  This would be a radical departure from old specs.  We don't need a huge reactor capable of 1000 MWatt/day.  Half that would likely be more than is necessary.  (Does anyone know any precise figures of power rating they're shooting for for reactor on a spaceship? I can try to get one from my prof, but I figured it might already be released.)<br>
<br>
2)Fraz: I agree with the main emphasis of your point about the biological effects of radiation that are not simply death.  However, I would like to note that Kiev was not downwind from the fallout of Chernobyl.  It was 80 miles away, and the people were largely fine.  Should it have been downwind at that time...who knows.  At 80 miles, it would have been left to a great number of factors to determine what effect,if any,the fallout would have.  Generally fallout is only a critical concern within a 10-mile radius, and major concern within 50-mile radius.  Up to 100 miles would be notified ASAP and possibly evacuated.  As stated above...80 miles could've been rather &quot;up in the air&quot;(no pun in intended, especially so somber a one as that would be). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 718<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/2/02 2:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What is stopping good systems?</span><hr size=1> 1)I'm glad we agree that Power reactors are fueled with tons of U235. You can get a whole heck of a lot of fission products out of that.<br>
As to your question:<br>
The NERVA Phoebus nuclear engine produced 4.5 gigawatts thermal power. A typical power plant reactor produces about 2 to 3.5 gigawatts(thermal). The Phoebus is the most powerful nuclear reactor ever run. <br>
It produced 250,000 pounds of thrust.<br>
It scales quite directly to other thrusts.<br>
<br>
A 2.5 million pound thrust booster - a middle of the road kind of launcher - would require an engine (or cluster) producing FORTY FIVE gigawatts(thermal).<br>
<br>
A reactor rocket in space would not need to be anywhere near this size AND would harm only its payload in an accident.<br>
<br>
<br>
Also the precise causes for TMI-2's destruction are irrelevent (altho a nuclear rocket does not even HAVE an ECCS). It is sufficient that it demonstrate that reactors are not reliable enough to justify a ground launch. TMI-2 would have been a national catastrophe if it were not for the effects of parts of it's Defense-in-Depth, which would not exist in a nuclear rocket.<br>
<br>
2) The distances you give are for protection primarily against ACUTE radiation poisoning, not cancers and other long-term health effects.<br>
<br>
<br>
yale<br>
