<br>
The basic general statement I'd make is that in regard to specifically this thread, I'd have to say that nuclear boosters are not as safe as chemical.  Looking for alternatives in methods of getting craft into space is a great idea, but i don't think the solution is any kind of a nuclear detonation.  As for nuclear reactors...they're just not designed for that short of a burst of energy; rather, reactors are good for sustained energy over time at fairly high levels.<br>
<br>
The booster to get into space should be chemical or other.  Then switch over to nuclear power when in space, and possibly nuclear propulsion if done correctly and alternative means seem to not work too well.<br>
<br>
I'm not in favor of any system that uses nuclear detonations, especially in the atmosphere of our planet or another planet but also including systems for use in space transit between locations.<br>
<br>
I'm whole-heartedly in favor of controlled nuclear reactions and utilizing a new reactor technology in coordination with a propulsion mechanism somehow. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 722<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/2/02 9:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What is stopping good systems?</span><hr size=1> The VASIMR electric engine, regardless of power source (solar, nuclear, whatever) seems to me an almost perfect machine (if its challenging engineering is successful).<br>
