space transit between locations</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Why ever can't it be used in space? What reason for banning atomic detonations for spacecraft propulsion in deep space?<br>
For me, it's a fundamental question of value. Is the kind of rapid interplanetary space travel that Orion would allow of high enough value that NPR ships should be built? The answer seems plain enough for me, but you seem to feel otherwise, so I'd like to hear it.<br>
<br>
I have my serious doubts about ever being able to make small blasts with no fallout (such as fusion only), so largely, I have to agree about the ground launch.<br>
 I might hold out some hope for pulse units that are clean enough to guarantee safety in the case of a high atmospheric upper stage NPR ship (Like the Saturn-V upper stage design).<br>
<br>
<br>
I still want to hear more about the possibillity of using the 11-Boron7 plus proton reaction. Does anybody ahve specifics?<br>
 Something like this: take a molecule made up of 11 atoms of  the isotope 7Bo, and bombard it with a certain number of protons. The reaction goes straight to produce extremely energetic ionized He, and no other particles.<br>
A high energy blast, with no fallout at all. <p>"Of course power corrupts -what else is it for?" Dominar Rygel XVI of the Hynerian empire</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 71<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/5/02 4:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: applications for nuclear engines</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Why ever can't it be used in space? What reason for banning atomic detonations for spacecraft propulsion in deep space?<br>
For me, it's a fundamental question of value. Is the kind of rapid interplanetary space travel that Orion would allow of high enough value that NPR ships should be built? The answer seems plain enough for me, but you seem to feel otherwise, so I'd like to hear it.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
How do you plan on decontaminating the craft?<br>
<br>
Lest we forget, there are a lot of radioactive byproducts from a nuclear explosion. Anytime the ship is to make an atmospheric landing, or people are going to do any routine maintenance in those areas, the entire ship will hafta get decon-ed.<br>
<br>
Also-stress limits.  What material will we develop that will hold a weld/joint through a series of dozens or hundreds of nuclear explosions?  Even if you develop a material that can take the peak stress load of this without failure, the fatigue put onto the materials would be rediculous.<br>
<br>
Lastly-&quot;wake&quot; effect.  Say you need to maneuver in close quarters to something,or another spacecraft strays behind you- An H-bomb propelled craft wouldn't be the friendliest thing to fly into the wake of.  Whereas other propulsion means might scald your craft or bombard you with EMP, a nuclear explosion would do significantly more.<br>
<br>
These are only my scientific arguments mind you.  I have my own set of moral objections to it as well, in the event that an alien species gets hold of the technology without having entered the nuclear age and we're responsible as a species for handing them nuclear bombs without any of the knowledge of the responsibility that goes with it, or creative uses rather than destructive.<br>
<br>
Interstellar speed would be a great thing.  Would it gain us much at this juncture though? &quot;hey, I'm a bunch of light years away from Earth! Boy, I sure wish I could call them to tell them my engine is out of order....but they're out of communications range.&quot;<br>
<br>
We need to develop other technologies in addition to propulsion, and by the time such technologies are developed we'll likely have something better than strapping yourself onto an explosive like Wile E. Coyote.  I'd hope so anyways. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umauk2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/5/02 7:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: applications for nuclear engines</span><hr size=1> Wow, what an interesting forum!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
projectorion, yales: You two are having lots of fun bludgeoning each other, but neither of you seems to be citing much in the way of facts.  Let's see what I can dredge up with a little creative google-ing.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Okay, first Chernobyl.  <br>
<br>
Chernobyl is hands down the most widely known major release of radiation in the world.  (It is possibly not the largest ever, but the details are unclear.)   Estimates vary widely, but in a worst case scenario the ENTIRE core burned and was dispersed!  This is 190 metric tonnes of fuel and graphite, and frankly I find it hard to believe the release was this total.  A more conservative estimate of the release is between 3 and 8 percent of the total activity of the core.  According to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/nucene/cherno2.html"> this site </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> this amounts to about 100 million curies, or 4 x 10^18 becquerels.<br>
<br>
Now, assuming 190,000 kilograms of fuel/moderator was present, 5 percent is 9,500 kilograms.  Note, much of the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nea.fr/html/rp/chernobyl/c02.html"> actual release </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> was very hot stuff indeed, the lighter weight, more volatile stuff, such as xenon, iodine, and cesium.  <br>
 <br>
Now, according to the first page linked above, estimates for total additional casualties due to Chernobyl range from 3000 to 17,000 additional deaths, above a baseline mortality of 9.5 million cancer deaths at the lower end of the range to 123 million cancer deaths at the upper end of the range.<br>
<br>
Or, the extra deaths range from 3/100'ths of a percent to 1/100'ths of a percent.<br>
<br>
Now, 17,000 deaths is bad, no doubt.  But a little perspective, please.  In the United States, digging coal kills about 1500 people a year due to black lung.  Let's not even consider worldwide deaths from mining coal.<br>
<br>
And, as long as we are discussing coal, kindly check out <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ornl.gov/ORNLReview/rev26-34/text/colmain.html"> this page. </a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->   According to this page, burning coal in the world in 1982 (20 years ago!) released 3640 tons of uranium!  Of that, 51,700 pounds was U-235.  This level of release has INCREASED since then.<br>
<br>
<br>
What is my point?  Radiation release is happening all the time.  Literally thousands of tons of uranium has been blown into the atmosphere in the last few hundred years.  In light of these facts, the incremental risk of using nuclear boosters is very, very small.  Given the benefits of getting off earth, they are very much worth taking.<br>
<br>
<br>
No hysteria, no rhetoric.  Facts.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, I have some thoughts on designing a nuclear booster as well, but that will have to be a different post.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 758<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/5/02 7:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Which is safer? Flying chernobyls or big fireworks</span><hr size=1> We discussed in other threads that:<br>
