 <p>"Every man has a right to his opinion, but no man has a right to be wrong in his facts." Bernard Baruch </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umauk2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/5/02 9:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Which is safer? Flying chernobyls or big fireworks</span><hr size=1> Arkuunaves: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  How do you plan on decontaminating the craft? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A simpler approach is to use low-activation materials.  IE, such exotic stuff as aluminum.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
If you will take a quick glance at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://ie.lbl.gov/education/parent/Al_iso.htm"> this page, </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> you will note that Aluminum has only two &quot;hot&quot; isotopes, Al28 and Al29.  (Al26 is also radioactive, but with a half-life of 700,000 years, I think we can handle the levels.)   Every other isotope decays within seconds, and are produced in much lower amounts by neutron activation.  (Since they are &quot;further away&quot; from the stable isotope.)<br>
<br>
Both Al28 and Al29 have very short half-lives, and decay though the benign beta-decay reaction.  <br>
<br>
So, build as much of your ship out of Aluminum as possible, and simple let it sit for a couple of hours if you need to go look at it.  2 hours is roughly 18 half lives of Al29.  It is basically GONE in that length of time.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Al 28 decays away to nothing even faster.  <br>
<br>
If you are extra worried, install a few tons of aluminum plates around your engines and replace them every few years.  (The beauty of nuclear engines is that you can AFFORD a few tons of aluminum plates.)<br>
<br>
There are other low activation materials as well, but Aluminum seems like such a good fit to build a spaceship out of....  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
